import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the CSV data into a DataFrame
df = pd.read_csv('IBM.csv')  # Replace 'IBM.csv' with your actual file name

# Extract the columns you want to plot
open_values = df['Open']
close_values = df['Close']

# Example: Plotting a pie chart for the first few rows of data
labels = df.index[:5]  # Assuming you want to plot the first 5 rows
sizes = close_values[:5]  # Replace 'Close' with the desired column
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Plotting the pie chart
plt.pie(sizes, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%')

plt.title('Pie Chart of Close Values')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the CSV data
df = pd.read_csv('IBM.csv')

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

# Plotting the 'Close' and 'Open' prices
plt.plot(df['Date'], df['Close'], label='Close Price')
plt.plot(df['Date'], df['Open'], label='Open Price')

# Labeling the axes
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Price')

# Adding a title
plt.title('IBM Stock Prices')

# Showing the legend
plt.legend()

# Display the plot
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the CSV data
df = pd.read_csv('IBM.csv')

# Set the figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

# Plotting 'Close' and 'Open' prices using seaborn
sns.lineplot(x='Date', y='Close', data=df, label='Close Price')
sns.lineplot(x='Date', y='Open', data=df, label='Open Price')

# Labeling the axes
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Price')

# Adding a title
plt.title('IBM Stock Prices')

# Displaying the legend
plt.legend()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the CSV data
df = pd.read_csv('IBM.csv')

# Select only the numeric columns for correlation
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include='number')

# Calculate the correlation matrix
corr_matrix = numeric_df.corr()

# Set the figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

# Create a heatmap with the correlation matrix
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, fmt='.2f', cmap='coolwarm')

# Add a title
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap of IBM Stock Data')

# Show the plot
plt.show()
